# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: emergency-exit
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:emergency-exit/1928-klm-fokker-f-iii-waalhaven-crash] On 24 July 1928, a KLM-owned Fokker F.III operated a scheduled passenger sightseeing flight from and back to Waalhaven Airport in Rotterdam, Netherlands.
[src:emergency-exit/1928-klm-fokker-f-iii-waalhaven-crash] The plane with the pilot and five passengers on board stalled shortly after takeoff and crashed after its landing gear and the right wing struck struck boats in the Waalhaven harbour next to the airport.
[src:emergency-exit/1928-klm-fokker-f-iii-waalhaven-crash] One passenger died after not all passengers could be saved in time while the airplane sank.
[src:emergency-exit/1928-klm-fokker-f-iii-waalhaven-crash] The pilot wasn’t properly trained for this older type of aircraft.
[src:emergency-exit/1928-klm-fokker-f-iii-waalhaven-crash] The passengers weren’t aware of the emergency hatch, and all could have survived had they used this emergency exit.
[src:emergency-exit/1928-klm-fokker-f-iii-waalhaven-crash] It was suggested to tell passengers before the flight where the emergency exit is located, which is nowadays one of the mandatory parts of the pre-flight safety demonstration.
[src:emergency-exit/1928-klm-fokker-f-iii-waalhaven-crash] Better visibility inside the cabin of the emergency exit was also advised.
[src:emergency-exit/1928-klm-fokker-f-iii-waalhaven-crash] The accident also resulted in better procedures by which pilots are assigned to fly certain aircraft types.
[src:emergency-exit/1928-klm-fokker-f-iii-waalhaven-crash] The involved airplane was a KLM-owned Fokker F.III with registration H-NABR and registration number 1533.
[src:emergency-exit/1928-klm-fokker-f-iii-waalhaven-crash] The plane had an Armstrong Siddeley Puma engine of 240 hp.
[src:emergency-exit/1928-klm-fokker-f-iii-waalhaven-crash] The aircraft had a cruising speed of 135 km/h (84 mph), a maximum take-off weight of 1,900 kg (4,200 lb), and a flight range of 1,000 km (620 mi).
[src:emergency-exit/1928-klm-fokker-f-iii-waalhaven-crash] In this type of aircraft, the pilot sat right next to the engine in the open air.
[src:emergency-exit/1928-klm-fokker-f-iii-waalhaven-crash] The aircraft was registered on 16 June 1922.
[src:emergency-exit/1928-klm-fokker-f-iii-waalhaven-crash] But the accident aircraft had a longer history, as it was built from the wreckage of H-NABL after its last crash.
[src:emergency-exit/1928-klm-fokker-f-iii-waalhaven-crash] The first was on 21 May 1921, in Hekelingen.
[src:emergency-exit/1928-klm-fokker-f-iii-waalhaven-crash] The hull was used for building a new airplane that was registered on 30 August 1921, under the same registration as H-NABL.
[src:emergency-exit/1928-klm-fokker-f-iii-waalhaven-crash] Hofstra of the H-NABL found himself lost and had to make a forced landing during the night in the darkness at Waalhaven Airport.
[src:emergency-exit/1928-klm-fokker-f-iii-waalhaven-crash] The plane flipped over due to poor lighting and was moderately damaged.
[src:emergency-exit/1928-klm-fokker-f-iii-waalhaven-crash] The accident aircraft was built from the wreckage of H-NABL.
[src:emergency-exit/1928-klm-fokker-f-iii-waalhaven-crash] On 9 July 1924, the H-NABR was the first KLM aircraft to transport livestock.
[src:emergency-exit/1928-klm-fokker-f-iii-waalhaven-crash] As there was foot and mouth disease in Belgium at the time, the breeding bull “Nico II” was transported by air from Waalhaven Airport to Paris.
[src:emergency-exit/1928-klm-fokker-f-iii-waalhaven-crash] In July 1928, the Rotterdamsche Aero Club organized, together with KLM, a three-day aviation festival at Waalhaven Airport.
[src:emergency-exit/1928-klm-fokker-f-iii-waalhaven-crash] On 24 July 1928, the Fokker F.III registered H-NABR was used as a sightseeing flight above Rotterdam from Waalhaven Airport, the Netherlands.
[src:emergency-exit/1928-klm-fokker-f-iii-waalhaven-crash] Besides the pilot, Scott, there were five female passengers on board.
[src:emergency-exit/1928-klm-fokker-f-iii-waalhaven-crash] After the usual test of the engine, the plane departed at 2:48 p.m. local time in a westerly direction.
[src:emergency-exit/1928-klm-fokker-f-iii-waalhaven-crash] After 150 meters in the air, the airplane flew in an abnormal position with a low-hanging tail.
[src:emergency-exit/1928-klm-fokker-f-iii-waalhaven-crash] Due to a sudden wind, the airplane drifted to the right.
[src:emergency-exit/1928-klm-fokker-f-iii-waalhaven-crash] The airplane flew just over the fence of the airport.
[src:emergency-exit/1928-klm-fokker-f-iii-waalhaven-crash] Due to the stalled position of the aircraft, the main landing gear and the right wing struck boats at the Waalhaven harbor.
[src:emergency-exit/1928-klm-fokker-f-iii-waalhaven-crash] The front three masts of the *Kolenmijn* were hit.
[src:emergency-exit/1928-klm-fokker-f-iii-waalhaven-crash] The first mast snapped off, the second mast lost the top part, and the third mast damaged the wing.
[src:emergency-exit/1928-klm-fokker-f-iii-waalhaven-crash] The plane glided seventy-five meters further away into the water of the harbor.
[src:emergency-exit/1928-klm-fokker-f-iii-waalhaven-crash] As the depth of the water was only four meters, the hull and left wing were at an angle above the water, and the right-wing was at the bottom of the water.
[src:emergency-exit/1928-klm-fokker-f-iii-waalhaven-crash] Rowing boats from surrounding ships went to the wreck to help.
[src:emergency-exit/1928-klm-fokker-f-iii-waalhaven-crash] The pilot and four passengers were released shortly after.
[src:emergency-exit/1928-klm-fokker-f-iii-waalhaven-crash] The position of the airplane changed all the time as the rescue was ongoing.
[src:emergency-exit/1928-klm-fokker-f-iii-waalhaven-crash] After most of the passengers were released, the cabin was almost entirely underwater.
[src:emergency-exit/1928-klm-fokker-f-iii-waalhaven-crash] The two oldest passengers were the last two people in the airplane and were seriously injured.
[src:emergency-exit/1928-klm-fokker-f-iii-waalhaven-crash] Pieter Guilonard, KLM’s chief of technical services, jumped in the water, kicked in the emergency exit, and ripped open the linen of the hull.
[src:emergency-exit/1928-klm-fokker-f-iii-waalhaven-crash] Twenty minutes after the crash, he managed to release the unconscious fifth passenger through the exit (some sources stated it was Madam Kappeyne who was saved last).
[src:emergency-exit/1928-klm-fokker-f-iii-waalhaven-crash] After long mouth-to-mouth resuscitation, she was declared dead.
[src:emergency-exit/1928-klm-fokker-f-iii-waalhaven-crash] With the help of Driessen, an engineer from KLM, the aircraft was pulled out of the water by *De Tweeling* and placed on the deck of the ship.
[src:emergency-exit/1928-klm-fokker-f-iii-waalhaven-crash] The river police seized the aircraft, which was later handed over to KLM.
[src:emergency-exit/1928-klm-fokker-f-iii-waalhaven-crash] There were six people on board: the pilot and five female passengers.
[src:emergency-exit/1928-klm-fokker-f-iii-waalhaven-crash] The passengers hadn’t known the location of the emergency hatch in the ceiling of the aircraft.
[src:emergency-exit/1928-klm-fokker-f-iii-waalhaven-crash] It was stated that all could have survived if they had used the emergency exit, as the exit was above the water for a long time.
[src:emergency-exit/1928-klm-fokker-f-iii-waalhaven-crash] It was suggested that passengers should be told before a flight where the emergency exit is located.
[src:emergency-exit/1928-klm-fokker-f-iii-waalhaven-crash] As KLM had high safety standards, the airline was criticized in the media for using its older airplanes for passenger flights.
[src:emergency-exit/1928-klm-fokker-f-iii-waalhaven-crash] Their recommendation was to establish better procedures under which pilots are assigned to fly certain types of aircraft.
[src:emergency-exit/1928-klm-fokker-f-iii-waalhaven-crash] Another recommendation was better visibility of the emergency exit.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] The **Airbus A330neo** ("neo" for "New Engine Option") is a wide-body airliner developed by Airbus from the original Airbus A330 (now A330*ceo* – "Current Engine Option").
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] A new version with modern engines comparable with those developed for the Boeing 787 was called for by operators of the A330ceo.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] It was launched on 14 July 2014 at the Farnborough Airshow, promising 14% better fuel economy per seat.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] It is exclusively powered by the Rolls-Royce Trent 7000 which has double the bypass ratio of its predecessor.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] The -900 made its maiden flight on 19 October 2017 and received its EASA type certificate on 26 September 2018; it was first delivered to TAP Air Portugal on 26 November 2018 and entered service on 15 December.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] The -800 made its first flight on 6 November 2018 and received EASA type certification on 13 February 2020; the first two -800s were delivered to Kuwait Airways on 29 October 2020 and entered service on 20 November.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] As of May 2026, a total of 474 A330neo family aircraft had been ordered by more than 30 customers, of which 195 aircraft had been delivered.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] At the Boeing 787 launch in 2004, Airbus' initial response was an improved A330.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] After negative feedback from airlines and lessors, the A350 XWB became a new design in 2006.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] After the A320neo launch in December 2010 and its commercial success, the largest airline of Malaysia, AirAsia – an all-Airbus operator – asked Airbus to re-engine the A330.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] New engines like the GEnx or Rolls-Royce Trent 1000 developed for the 787 could offer a 12%–15% fuel burn improvement, and sharklets at least 2%.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] Airbus sales chief John Leahy's argument was that the lower purchase price of an A330 even without new engines make the economics of buying an A330 competitive at midrange routes with that of the Boeing 787.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] An A330neo would accelerate the demise of the similarly sized A350-800.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] Airbus also considered re-engining the A380 but was wary of having two major modification programs simultaneously.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] In March 2014, Delta Air Lines expressed an interest in the A330neo to replace its ageing, 20+-year-old Boeing 767-300ER jets.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] In the 250-300-seat market, CIT Group believed an A330neo enables profitability on shorter ranges where the longer-range A350 and Boeing 787 are not optimised.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] CIT said that the A350-800 was not as efficient as it would like, and Air Lease Corp. added that the company did not consider it reasonable to take the A350-800 and A330neo as they saw no sustainable coexistence of the two aircraft.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] AirAsia X ended flights to London and Paris from Kuala Lumpur in 2012 because their Airbus A340s were not fuel-efficient enough and would try again with A330s.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] As Airbus gradually increased the output of the new A350, prolonging the production run of the A330 could help to maintain profitability.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] After Emirates cancelled 70 orders for the A350, Airbus said it continued to work on re-engining the smaller A330.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] On 14 July 2014 at the Farnborough Airshow, Airbus launched the A330neo programme, to be powered by the new Rolls-Royce Trent 7000.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] It would improve the fuel burn per seat by 14%.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] Airbus hoped to sell 1,000 A330neo aircraft.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] Its range would increase by 400 nautical miles (740 km; 460 mi) and although 95% of the parts would be common with the A330ceo, maintenance costs would be lower.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] New winglets, 3.7 metres wider and similar to those of the A350 XWB, still within ICAO category E airport requirements, along with new engine pylons, would improve aerodynamics by 4%.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] The A330neo's development costs, an estimated $2 billion (£1.18 billion) , were expected to have an impact of around −0.7% on Airbus's return on sales target from 2015 to 2017.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] Airbus stated that lower capital cost would make the A330neo the most cost-efficient medium-range wide-body airliner.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] Airbus said that it could pursue demand for 4,000 aircraft and that there was an open market for 2,600 jets not already addressed by backlogs with operators already using A330s.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] Aerodynamic modifications would include a re-twisted wing and optimised slats.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] In 2014, *The Airline Monitor'*s Ed Greenslet stated that the A330neo would have the advantage of not being designed to fly 8,000 nmi, unlike the A350 and Boeing 787 which were thus less economical on shorter routes, although "the vast majority of long-haul markets is 4,000 nmi or less".
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] John Leahy estimated that the A330-900 would have operating costs on par with the 787-9, but would be available at 25% lower capital costs and could reach a production rate of 10 per month after a 7/8 per month rate at the production start.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] Both A330neo variants were expected to have a maximum take-off weight of 242 t.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] The type design was frozen in late 2015.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] On 7 September 2015, Airbus announced that it had begun production of the first A330neo with the construction of its centre wingbox and engine pylon.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] Final assembly of the first aircraft, an A330-900, started in September 2016 at the Airbus Toulouse site with the joining of the wings to the centre fuselage at the station 40.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] In December 2016, the programme schedule slipped by six weeks due to marginal engine development at Rolls-Royce, and launch customer TAP Air Portugal projected its first A330neo would be delivered in March 2018.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] The first aircraft left the paint shop in December 2016, awaiting its engines.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] By April 2017, the Trent 7000s were to be installed later during the summer so that the first flight was delayed until September.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] Due to the delay, TAP Air Portugal was not expected to receive the first A330neo until the end of the first half of 2018, or even in the third quarter.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] The engines were shipped to Airbus in June.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] The aircraft complete with engines showed at Toulouse in September before its first flight.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] Major structures of the first A330-800 were entering production in October 2017: high-lift devices are installed on the wing in Bremen, fuselage sections are built in Hamburg, the centre wing-box in Nantes, titanium engine pylons in Toulouse and sharklet wingtips in Korea.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] Its final assembly started in November 2017, on track for its planned first flight in mid-2018.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] Structural assembly was completed by February 2018, having its flight-test instruments installed and waiting for its engines before its 300h flight-test programme.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] At this time, production aircraft progressed through the final assembly line with the first 'Airspace' cabin interior being fitted.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] A330 production was cut to 50 deliveries in 2019, with more than half of them re-engined A330neos.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] In April 2020, the production rate decreased from 3.5 to 2 per month due to the impact of the COVID-19 pandemic on aviation, and finished planes were stored while waiting for deferred deliveries.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] The A330-900 first flight on 19 October 2017 was a debut of the 1,400 hours flight test campaign involving three prototypes plus the first production aircraft: 1,100 flight hours for the A330-900 and 300 flight hours for the A330-800, targeting mid-2018 EASA and FAA Type Certification.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] It should establish certain maximum operating points and achieve an initial handling qualities assessment including at high angle of attack.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] This first aircraft, MSN1795, was scheduled to perform 600 h and was to be joined the following month by the second, MSN1813, which will fly 500 h, before the third, MSN1819, the first customer aircraft for TAP Portugal with a complete cabin.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] Two flight test engineers and two engine specialists monitored the 60GB per hour output of 1,375 sensors and 98,000 parameters, including strips of microelectromechanical systems to measure aerodynamic pressure distribution across the wing.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] MSN1795 was to undertake simulated icing tests and cold-weather tests in Canada, noise assessment, autoland testing and high angle-of-attack, minimum-unstick checks during rotation with a tail bumper.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] MSN1813 was to test natural icing conditions, assess hot and high conditions in the United Arab Emirates and La Paz, and fly 150h of route-proving; it has rakes and pressure sensors in the engine flows to compare actual thrust with ground bench measurements.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] MSN1819 was to validate the Airspace cabin interior fitting with artificial passengers for ventilation analysis and cabin environment measurements.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] The second test aircraft made its maiden flight on 4 December, to be used to validate aerodynamic & engine performance and airline operations.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] By the end of January 2018, the first logged almost 200h in 58 flights while the second had accumulated nearly 120h in 30 flights.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] Its flight envelope was fully opened including flutter and stall tests to complete powerplant calibration and strake configuration has been frozen.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] Airbus commenced autopilot, autoland and high-speed performance testing, and was to move on to hot- and cold-weather tests, as well as noise and icing tests, over the following three months.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] As of 10 April 2018, the two test aircraft had logged over 200 flights and more than 700 hours, testing −27 °C cold weather, natural icing, crosswind landing, 37 °C and 8,000 ft (2,400 m) hot and high operations.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] The first TAP Air Portugal aircraft made its first flight on 15 May 2018; it joined the two previous test aircraft to check the cabin systems: air conditioning, crew rest, etc.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] It started the final certification step on 18 June: function and reliability tests or route proving, including ETOPS, diversion airport landing, and testing ground handling over 150 flight test hours, as the flight test programme reached 1,000 hours.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] Entry into service was planned for the third quarter of 2018 and ETOPS was to be approved in October for 330min.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] EASA granted the A330-941 type certificate on 26 September 2018, with ETOPS not yet approved.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] ETOPS 180 min was approved on 14 November, restricted to engines with fewer than 500 flight cycles.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] Airbus expects the FAA type certification with 180 min ETOPS by the end of 2018 and 330 min ETOPS in the first half of 2019.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] Beyond-180min ETOPS was approved by the EASA on 24 January 2019.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] The maiden flight of the -800 took place on 6 November 2018; the 4h 4min flight inaugurated a 350h test program aiming for mid-2019 type certification, for delivery in the first half of 2020 to launch operator Kuwait Airways.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] By late March 2019, it was halfway through the 300-hour flight test programme, having completed 44 flights in 149 hours.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] The -800 received EASA type certification with 180-minute ETOPS on 13 February 2020; ETOPS clearance beyond 180 minutes was awarded on 2 April.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] Leased from Avolon, the first A330-900 was delivered to TAP Air Portugal on 26 November 2018, featuring 298 seats: 34 full-flat business, 96 economy plus and 168 economy seats, and to be deployed from Portugal to the Americas and Africa.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] TAP made its first commercial flight on 15 December from Lisbon to São Paulo.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] The airline should receive 15 more A330neos in 2019 and fly the A330-900 from Lisbon to Chicago O'Hare and Washington Dulles from June 2019, both five times a week.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] On the occasion of the 19 October 2017 first flight, an increase to 251 t (553,000 lb) MTOW by mid-2020 was announced, with a few changes to the landing gear and brakes, increasing its range by 700 or 1,000 nmi (1,300 or 1,900 km) compared to the current A330neo or A330ceo.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] The 251 t MTOW was confirmed by Airbus in November 2017.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] Test flights of the 251 t A330-900 started from 28 February 2020.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] Airbus was expecting a short 30–40h test campaign, as multiple tests were conducted with the previous variant adapted to higher weight, including flight performance and noise assessment.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] The heavier structure allows a transpacific range and is balanced by a weight-reduction effort, keeping the same empty weight and payload.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] On 8 October 2020, the 251 t A330-900 was EASA-certified, before introduction by Corsair International.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] Retaining 99% spares commonality, it offers 6 t (13,000 lb) more payload while strengthening the landing-gear and extending the time before overhaul interval from 10 to 12 years.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] On 31 March 2021, Corsair took delivery of the first 251t Airbus A330-900 in a three-class, 352-seat configuration.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] The 251 t A330-800 was certified by EASA in April 2022.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] On 11 June 2025, Airbus planned for 2028 a 253 t (558,000 lb) variant, while a 68,000 lbf (320 kN) thrust rating should be available from 2026.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] The Civil Aviation Administration of China (CAAC) granted the A330neo family its Validation of Type Certificate (VTC) in December 2024.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] Hainan Airlines hinted towards ordering 20 A330-900s with an order for galley parts from Safran in March 2024, while Hong Kong-based Cathay Pacific placed a firm order for 30 A330-900s later that August.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] The A330neo is advertised as having a 12% fuel burn advantage per flight over the older A330 variants.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] This advantage comes from the 11% gain from the Trent 7000 and its larger 112-inch fan, compared to the 97.5-inch Trent 700 engine.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] However, this gain is negated by 3%–2% by additional weight, and 1% due to engine drag, but the sharklets and aero optimization regain 4%, restoring the advantage to 12%.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] Furthermore, fuel consumption per seat is improved by 2% due to the rearranged cabin (Space-Flex and Smart-Lav) with increased seating, offering a 14% fuel burn reduction per seat for the new −900 compared to the previous 235-tonne −300 version.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] The newer 242-tonne −300 is already 2% more efficient.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] Since the fan is enlarged from 97 to 112 in (250 to 280 cm), the nacelles are mounted higher, necessitating extensive CFD analysis to avoid supersonic shock wave interference drag, as is the first slat's dog-tooth.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] The wing twist and belly fairings are tweaked to approach the lowest drag elliptical span-wise pressure distribution changed by the larger sharklets, like the flap track fairings shape to lower form drag.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] Initially based on the largest 242t MTOW A330, Airbus was studying an improvement to 245 t (540,000 lb) MTOW for the A330neo, which would match the figure originally given for the Airbus A350-800 before it was sidelined in favor of the A330neo.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] The redesigned interior, dubbed "Airspace" by Airbus and unveiled in 2016, received larger overhead bins, new ceiling panels with customisable patterns, and updated lighting.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] Many design elements were incorporated from the A350.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] The cockpit windows feature a black "mask" outline, similar to the A350.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] Candidate engines included variants of Rolls-Royce's Trent 1000 and General Electric's GEnx-1B.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] Both engine makers were reportedly interested in winning an exclusive deal should a re-engined A330 be offered.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] The Trent 1000 TEN (Thrust, Efficiency, New Technology) engine was under development for the 787-10, but Rolls-Royce intended to offer a broad power range.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] The A330neo uses the Rolls-Royce Trent 7000 engine, which is an electronic controlled bleed air variant of the Trent 1000 used on the Boeing 787-10.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] It will have a 112 in (284 cm) diameter fan and a 10:1 bypass ratio.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] The Trent is the exclusive powerplant, as Rolls-Royce offered better terms to obtain exclusivity.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] The decision to offer the aircraft with only one engine option is not unique to Airbus; the Boeing 777X will come equipped exclusively with General Electric GE9X engines, after Rolls-Royce made a bid with its Advance configuration but was not selected.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] The A330-800 retains the fuselage length of the A330-200, but can seat six more passengers (for a total of 252) with an optimised cabin featuring 18-inch-wide economy seats.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] As the variants share 99% commonality, developing the smaller -800 has a negligible extra cost.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] After the first flight of the -900 on 19 October 2017, Hawaiian Airlines (then the only customer for the -800) considered changing its order to six -800s, seeking best to fit its current network to Asia and North America whilst allowing for future growth, possibly to Europe.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] In contrast, the -200 commanded 40% of the CEO deliveries: its range advantage has eroded with the increased capabilities of the -900, and although it offers lower fuel use per trip, fuel use per seat is higher.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] As of 2017, demand for the -800 was limited by low fuel prices and the -200s it might replace after 2020 were still young (nine years on average).
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] The Boeing 767-300s that the -800 might replace are 15 years older, and while Boeing considered relaunching production of the 767-300ER, mainly as an interim for American and United Airlines, this was complicated by a 30-year-old design including obsolete cabin amenities.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] At this time, Boeing intended to launch its New Midsize Airplane no earlier than 2027, affording Airbus opportunities with the 95 operators of the A330ceo.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] Production of the -800 beyond the prototype was in doubt, as Hawaiian was choosing between the Airbus A350-900 and the Boeing 787-8/9.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] In February 2018, Hawaiian was thought to be cancelling its order for six A330-800s, replacing them with Boeing 787-9s priced at less than $100–115m, close to their production cost of $80–90m, while Boeing Capital released Hawaiian from three 767-300ER leases well in advance.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] Hawaiian denied that the order for the A330-800 had been cancelled, but did not dismiss a new deal with Boeing.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] In March 2018, Hawaiian confirmed the cancellation of its order for six A330-800s and ordered ten B787-9s instead.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] Airbus says it was "simply undercut in price".
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] In July 2018, a new memorandum of understanding from Uganda Airlines for two -800s revived interest in the shorter variant.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] On 8 April 2019, Uganda National Airlines Company firmed up its order for two -800s.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] Airbus could limit its MTOW to 200 t (440,000 lb) and derate its engines to 68,000 lbf (300,000 N) to optimise for the shorter routes to be targeted by the Boeing NMA, with the A321XLR tackling the lower end of the same niche.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] The A330-800 received EASA type certification on 13 February 2020.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] The first aircraft, configured with 226 seats including 23 in business class, was to be delivered to Kuwait Airways in March, but the airline postponed delivery until the third quarter of 2020 amid the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] On 29 October, the first two A330-800s were delivered to Kuwait Airways; the airline had six more -800s on order but subsequently decided to switch to the -900, becoming the first airline to operate both variants.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] The A330-800 then operated its first revenue flight on 20 November, flying the short distance between Kuwait and Dubai.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] Uganda Airlines received their first A330-800 on 21 December, with the second unit expected in January 2021.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] Air Greenland took delivery of its only A330-800, named *Tuukkaq*, on 6 December 2022 and entered service on 19 December 2022 as a replacement for their Airbus A330-200, *Norsaq*.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] As of March 2024, there are only seven A330-800s in revenue service with just three operators; Kuwait Airways is the largest operator with four aircraft in its fleet.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] Garuda Indonesia was the fourth airline to order four A330-800s but the order was later cancelled.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] The A330-900 retains the fuselage length of the A330-300 and the similarly sized four-engined A340-300.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] Cabin optimisation allows ten additional seats on the A330-900 (310 passengers) with 18-inch-wide economy seats.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] Delta expects a 20 percent reduction in operating cost per seat over the Boeing 767-300ER aircraft it replaces.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] Further reconfiguration of cabin facilities enables the –900 to seat up to 460 passengers in an all-economy layout.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] This exceeds the existing 440-seat maximum exit limit allowed by the type certificate, and requires a modification of the Type-A exit doors to meet emergency exit requirements.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] In November 2019, maximum accommodation increased to 460 seats, through the installation of new 'Type-A+' exits, with a dual-lane evacuation slide.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] Amazon Air and UPS Airlines pushed for a freighter version, stretching the A330-900 to carry more cargo over a shorter range, but it competes with the cheaper option of converting readily available retired passenger 767 and A330 aircraft.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] Development costs for the proposed freighter would be lower than for a new program, as much of the engineering has already been done for the A330-200F.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] Airbus formally launched the tanker variant of the A330neo, dubbed as the A330 MRTT+, at the 2024 Farnborough International Airshow.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] The A330 MRTT+ is based on the A330-800 and is intended to replace the A330 MRTT.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] The A330 MRTT+ also retains the 111,000 kg (245,000 lb) fuel capacity of the A330 MRTT.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] Airbus plans to deliver the first A330 MRTT+ in 2029.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] The launch customer is expected to be the Royal Thai Air Force.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] Airbus launched the business version of the A330neo, known as the ACJ330neo.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] It can carry a maximum of 25 passengers and can fly up to 10,400 nautical miles in 21 hours without refueling.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] There are two versions of the business jet which are the ACJ330-800 and the ACJ330-900 and there are four cabin outfits.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] Below is a list of major differences between the A330neo variants.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] There are 195 aircraft in service with 25 operators as of May 2026.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] The five largest operators of A330neo are Delta Air Lines (39), TAP Air Portugal (19), Condor (18), ITA Airways (16) and Cebu Pacific (14).
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] On 11 April 2023, Airbus delivered the 100th A330neo, an A330-900, to German airline Condor Flugdienst GmbH, which would lease it from AerCap.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] At that time, the A330neo Family flew in the liveries of 22 airlines on over 200 routes and destinations worldwide.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] They have close economics but the A330neo costs up to $30m less, according to another publication.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] An A330-900 is worth $115 million in 2018, while a new B787-9 valuation is $145 million, up from $135 million in 2014, but it may have been sold for $110–15 million to prevent A330neo sales.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] Between the 2004 launch of the Dreamliner and the A330neo launch in 2014, the market was split almost equally between both, with between 900 and 920 A330ceos sold against 950 to 1,000 787-8/9s.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] Between 2014 and the neo first flight in October 2017, the A330/A330neo had 440 orders (excluding freighters) compared to 272 for the 787-8/9 (excluding the -10), or since the 787 launch, 1211 A330ceo/neos compared to 1106 787-8/9s.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] Teal Group's Richard Aboulafia believes that the A330neo should dominate the lower range and lower capacity end of the twin aisle market because the 787-8 has the high operating economics and unit price associated with its 8,000-nm range.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] Flightglobal Ascend Consultancy forecast 600 deliveries including 10% of -800 variants, less optimistic than Airbus's 1,000.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] At entry into service in 2018, sales were disappointing and A330 production was to be cut to 50 in 2019 down from 67 in 2017: while it was the widebody with the largest operator base with 1,390 deliveries since 1993, the fleet was still very young with only 46 aircraft retired.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] Airbus believed A330 operators would start fleet renewal beginning in 2020.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] With the exception of Delta, industry-leading airlines preferred the Boeing 787.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] Between January 2014 and November 2019, the A330/A330neo had 477 net orders (net of cancellations) compared to a total of 407 for all three variants of the 787.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] The A330neo program was the best-selling Airbus widebody over the same period.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] Airbus believes there is potential for the A330neo in the growing long-haul, low-cost carrier sector.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] While Airbus expected a market for over 1,000 A330neos, one pessimistic forecast reported in 2018 came in as low as 400 sales, in that the A330neo was late to the market and fuel prices had declined markedly over the years, reducing demand.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] As of June 2018, 19% of A330 operators also operate the Boeing 787.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] Leeham News argued that the A330-800 does not fully cover the upper end of Boeing's studied New Midsize Airplane market, while also describing the A330-800 as a cost-effective entry for Airbus into the upper end of the middle of the market.
[src:emergency-exit/a330neo] In May 2019, Airbus's chief commercial officer made clear the company has a “rock”, the A321neo, and a “hard place”, the A330-800, for any airframer intending to bring a new airplane into the middle of the market at a time when Boeing was mired in the 737 MAX crisis.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The **Airbus A350** is a long-range, wide-body twin-engine airliner developed and produced by Airbus.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The initial A350 design, which was proposed in 2004, in response to the Boeing 787 Dreamliner, would have been a development of the Airbus A330 with composite wings, advanced winglets, and new efficient engines.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Due to inadequate market support, Airbus switched in 2006 to a clean-sheet extra wide body (XWB) design, powered by two Rolls-Royce Trent XWB high bypass turbofan engines.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The prototype first flew on 14 June 2013 from Toulouse, France.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Type certification from the European Aviation Safety Agency (EASA) was obtained in September 2014, followed by certification from the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) two months later.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The A350 is the first Airbus aircraft largely made of carbon-fibre-reinforced polymers.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The fuselage is designed around a 3-3-3 nine-across economy cross-section, an increase from the eight-across A330/A340 2-4-2 configuration.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] (The A350 has 3-4-3 ten-across economy seating on select aircraft.) It has a common type rating with the A330.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] On 15 January 2015, the first A350-900 entered service with Qatar Airways, followed by the A350-1000 on 24 February 2018 with the same launch operator.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] As of May 2026, Singapore Airlines is the largest operator with 65 aircraft in its fleet, while Turkish Airlines is the largest customer with 110 aircraft on order.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] A total of 1,595 A350 family aircraft have been ordered, of which 718 units have been delivered and 717 units are in service with 38 operators.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The global A350 fleet has completed more than 2 million flights on more than 1,365 routes, transporting more than 530 million passengers with no fatalities and one hull loss in an airport-safety-related incident.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] It succeeds the A340 and competes against Boeing's large long-haul twinjets, the Boeing 777, its future successor, the 777X, and the 787 Dreamliner.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Airbus initially rejected Boeing's claim that the Boeing 787 Dreamliner would be a serious threat to the Airbus A330, stating that the 787 was just a reaction to the A330 and that no response was needed.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] When airlines urged Airbus to provide a competitor, Airbus initially proposed the "A330-200 Lite", a derivative of the A330 featuring improved aerodynamics and engines similar to those on the 787.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The company planned to announce this version at the 2004 Farnborough Airshow, but did not proceed.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] On 16 September 2004, Airbus president and chief executive officer Noël Forgeard confirmed the consideration of a new project during a private meeting with prospective customers.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Forgeard did not give a project name, and did not state whether it would be an entirely new design or a modification of an existing product.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Airline dissatisfaction with this proposal motivated Airbus to commit €4 billion to a new airliner design.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] On 10 December 2004, Airbus' shareholders, EADS and BAE Systems, approved the "authorisation to offer" for the A350, expecting a 2010 service entry.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Airbus then expected to win more than half of the 250-300-seat aircraft market, estimated at 3,100 aircraft overall over 20 years.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Fuel efficiency would improve by over 10% with a mostly carbon fibre reinforced polymer wing and initial General Electric GEnx-72A1 engines, before offering a choice of powerplant.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] It had a common fuselage cross-section with the A330 and also a new horizontal stabiliser.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] On 13 June 2005 at the Paris Air Show, Middle Eastern carrier Qatar Airways announced that they had placed an order for 60 A350s.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] In September 2006 the airline signed a memorandum of understanding with General Electric (GE) to launch the GEnx-1A-72 engine for the new airliner model.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Emirates sought a more improved design and decided against ordering the initial version of the A350.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] On 6 October 2005, the programme's industrial launch was announced with an estimated development cost of around €3.5 billion.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The A350 was initially planned to be a 250 to 300-seat twin-engine wide-body aircraft derived from the existing A330's design.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Under this plan, the A350 would have modified wings and new engines while sharing the A330's fuselage cross-section.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] For this design, the fuselage was to consist primarily of aluminium-lithium rather than the carbon-fibre-reinforced polymer (CFRP) fuselage on the Boeing 787.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The A350 would see entry in two versions: the A350-800 with a 8,800 nmi (16,300 km; 10,100 mi) range with a typical passenger capacity of 253 in a three-class configuration, and the A350-900 with 7,500 nmi (13,900 km; 8,600 mi) range and a 300-seat three-class configuration.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The A350 was designed to be a direct competitor to the Boeing 787-9 and 777-200ER.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The original A350 design was publicly criticised by two of Airbus's largest customers, International Lease Finance Corporation (ILFC) and GE Capital Aviation Services (GECAS).
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] On 28 March 2006, ILFC President Steven F.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Udvar-Házy urged Airbus to pursue a clean-sheet design or risk losing market share to Boeing and branded Airbus's strategy as "a Band-aid reaction to the 787", a sentiment echoed by GECAS president Henry Hubschman.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] In April 2006, while reviewing bids for the Boeing 787 and A350, the CEO of Singapore Airlines (SIA) Chew Choon Seng, commented that "having gone through the trouble of designing a new wing, tail, and cockpit, [Airbus] should have gone the whole hog and designed a new fuselage".
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Airbus responded that they were considering A350 improvements to satisfy customer demands.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] One such proposal, known internally as "1d", formed the basis of the A350 redesign.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] On 14 July 2006, during the Farnborough International Airshow, the redesigned aircraft was designated "A350 XWB" (Xtra-Wide-Body).
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Within four days, Singapore Airlines agreed to order 20 A350 XWBs with options for another 20 A350 XWBs.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The proposed A350 was a new design, including a wider fuselage cross-section, allowing seating arrangements ranging from an eight-across low-density premium economy layout to a ten-across high-density seating configuration for a maximum seating capacity of 440–475 depending on variant.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The A330 and previous iterations of the A350 would only be able to accommodate a maximum of eight seats per row.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The 787 is typically configured for nine seats per row.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The 777 accommodates nine or ten seats per row, with more than half of recent 777s being configured in a ten-across layout that will come standard on the 777X.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The A350 cabin is 12.7 cm (5.0 in) wider at the eye level of a seated passenger than the 787's cabin, and 28 cm (11 in) narrower than the Boeing 777's cabin (see the Wide-body aircraft comparison of cabin widths and seating).
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The redesigned composite fuselage allows for higher cabin pressure and humidity, and lower maintenance costs.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] On 1 December 2006, the Airbus board of directors approved the industrial launch of the A350-800, -900, and -1000 variants.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The delayed launch decision was a result of delays to the Airbus A380 and discussions on how to fund development.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] EADS CEO Thomas Enders stated that the A350 programme was not a certainty, citing EADS/Airbus's stretched resources.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] However, it was decided programme costs are to be borne mainly from cash-flow.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] First delivery for the A350-900 was scheduled for mid-2013, with the -800 and -1000 following on 12 and 24 months later, respectively.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] New technical details of the A350 XWB were revealed at a press conference in December 2006.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Chief operating officer, John Leahy indicated existing A350 contracts were being re-negotiated due to price increases compared to the original A350s contracted.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] On 4 January 2007, Pegasus Aviation Finance Company placed the first firm order for the A350 XWB with an order for two aircraft.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The design change imposed a two-year delay into the original timetable and increased development costs from US$5.5 billion (€5.3 billion) to approximately US$10 billion (€9.7 billion).
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] *Reuters* estimated the A350's total development cost at US$15 billion (€12 billion or £10 billion).
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The original mid-2013 delivery date of the A350 was changed, as a longer than anticipated development forced Airbus to delay the final assembly and first flight of the aircraft to the third quarter of 2012 and second quarter of 2013 respectively.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] As a result, the flight test schedule was compressed from the original 15 months to 12 months.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] A350 programme chief Didier Evrard stressed that delays only affected the A350-900 while the -800 and -1000 schedules remained unchanged.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Airbus' 2019 earnings report indicated the A350 programme had broken even that year.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Airbus suggested Boeing's use of composite materials for the 787 fuselage was premature, and that the new A350 XWB was to feature carbon fibre panels only for the main fuselage skin.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] However, after facing criticism for maintenance costs, Airbus confirmed in early September 2007 that it would also use carbon fibre for fuselage frames.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The composite frames would feature aluminium strips to ensure the electrical continuity of the fuselage, for dissipating lightning strikes.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Airbus used a full mock up fuselage to develop the wiring, a different approach from the A380, on which the wiring was all done on computers.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] In 2006, Airbus confirmed development of a full bleed air system on the A350, as opposed to the 787's bleedless configuration.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Rolls-Royce agreed with Airbus to supply a new variant of the Trent turbofan engine for the A350 XWB, named *Trent XWB*.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] In 2010, after low-speed wind tunnel tests, Airbus finalised the static thrust at sea level for all three proposed variants to the 74,000–94,000 lbf (330–420 kN) range.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] GE stated it would not offer the GP7000 engine on the aircraft, and that previous contracts for the GEnx on the original A350 did not apply to the XWB.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Engine Alliance partner Pratt & Whitney seemed to be unaligned with GE on this, having publicly stated that it was looking at an advanced derivative of the GP7000.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] In April 2007, former Airbus CEO Louis Gallois held direct talks with GE management over developing a GEnx variant for the A350 XWB.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] In June 2007, John Leahy indicated that the A350 XWB would not feature the GEnx engine, saying that Airbus wanted GE to offer a more efficient version for the airliner.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Since then, the largest GE engines operators, which include Emirates, US Airways, Hawaiian Airlines and ILFC have selected the Trent XWB for their A350 orders.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] In May 2009, GE said that if it were to reach a deal with Airbus to offer the current 787-optimised GEnx for the A350, it would only power the -800 and -900 variants.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] GE believed it could offer a product that outperforms the Trent 1000 and Trent XWB, but was reluctant to support an aircraft competing directly with its GE90-115B-powered 777 variants.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] In January 2008, French-based Thales Group won a US$2.9 billion (€2 billion) 20-year contract to supply avionics and navigation equipment for the A350 XWB, beating Honeywell and Rockwell Collins.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] US-based Rockwell Collins and Moog Inc. were chosen to supply the horizontal stabiliser actuator and primary flight control actuation, respectively.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The flight management system incorporated several new safety features.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Regarding cabin ergonomics and entertainment, in 2006 Airbus signed a firm contract with BMW for development of an interior concept for the original A350.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] On 4 February 2010, Airbus signed a contract with Panasonic Avionics Corporation to deliver in-flight entertainment and communication (IFEC) systems for the Airbus A350 XWB.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] In 2008, Airbus planned to start cabin furnishing early in parallel with final assembly to cut production time in half.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The A350 XWB production programme sees extensive international collaboration and investments in new facilities: Airbus constructed 10 new factories in Western Europe and the US, with extensions carried out on three further sites.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Among the new buildings was a £570 million (US$760 million or €745 million) composite facility in Broughton, Wales, which would be responsible for the wings.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] In June 2009, the National Assembly for Wales announced provision of a £28 million grant to provide a training centre, production jobs and money toward the new production centre.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Airbus manufactured the first structural component in December 2009.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Production of the first fuselage barrel began in late 2010 at its production plant in Illescas, Spain.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Construction of the first A350-900 centre wingbox was set to start in August 2010.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The new composite rudder plant in China opened in early 2011.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The forward fuselage of the first A350 was delivered to the final assembly plant in Toulouse on 29 December 2011.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Final assembly of the first A350 static test model was started on 5 April 2012.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Final assembly of the first prototype A350 was completed in December 2012.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The production rate was expected to rise from three aircraft per month in early 2015 to five at the end of 2015, and would ramp to ten aircraft per month by 2018.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] In 2015, 17 planes would be delivered and the initial dispatch reliability was 98%.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Airbus announced plans to increase its production rate from 10 monthly in 2018 to 13 monthly from 2019 and six A330 are produced monthly.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Around 90 deliveries were expected for 2018, with 15% or ≈14 units being A350-1000 variants.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] That year, 93 aircraft were delivered, three more than expected.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] In 2019, Airbus delivered 112 A350s (87 A350-900s and 25 A350-1000s) at a rate of 10 per month, and were going to keep the rate around nine to 10 per month, to reflect softer demand for widebodies, as the backlog reached 579 − or 5.2 years of production at a constant rate.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The COVID-19 pandemic caused the decrease of A350 production from 9.5 per month to six per month, since April 2020.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] After the pandemic a ramp-up is planned, aiming to reach a rate of 9 per month by the end of 2025.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] As the pre-pandemic rate of 10 monthly is aimed for by 2026, by April 2024 Airbus was planning a 12-monthly production rate by 2028 after securing 281 net orders in 2023.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The first Trent engine test was made on 14 June 2010.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The Trent XWB's flight test programme began use on the A380 development aircraft in early 2011, ahead of engine certification in late 2011.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] On 2 June 2013, the Trent XWB engines were powered up on the A350 for the first time.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Airbus confirmed that the flight test programme would last 12 months and use five test aircraft.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The A350's maiden flight took place on 14 June 2013 from the Toulouse–Blagnac Airport.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Airbus's chief test pilot said, "it just seemed really happy in the air...all the things we were testing had no major issues at all".
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] It flew for four hours, reaching Mach 0.8 at 25,000 feet after retracting the landing gear and starting a 2,500 h flight test campaign.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Costs for developing the aircraft were estimated at €11 billion (US$15 billion or £9.5 billion) in June 2013.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] 2 underwent two and a half weeks of climatic tests in the unique McKinley Climatic Laboratory at Eglin Air Force Base, Florida, in May 2014, and was subjected to multiple climatic and humidity settings from 45 °C (113 °F) to −40 °C (−40 °F).
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The A350 received type certification from the European Aviation Safety Agency (EASA) on 30 September 2014.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] On 15 October 2014, EASA approved the A350-900 for ETOPS (Extended-range Twin-engine Operations Performance Standards) 370, allowing it to fly more than six hours on one engine and making it the first airliner to be approved for "ETOPS Beyond 180 minutes" before entry into service.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Later that month Airbus received regulatory approval for a Common Type Rating for pilot training between the A350 XWB and A330.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] On 12 November 2014, the A350 received certification from the FAA.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] On 1 August 2017, the EASA issued an airworthiness directive mandating operators to power cycle (reset) early A350-900s before 149 hours of continuous power-on time, reissued in July 2019.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] In June 2011, the A350-900 was scheduled to enter service in the first half of 2014, with the -800 to enter service in mid-2016, and the -1000 in 2017.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] In July 2012, Airbus delayed the -900's introduction by three months to the second half of 2014.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The delivery to launch customer Qatar Airways took place on 22 December 2014.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The first commercial flight was made on 15 January 2015 between Doha and Frankfurt.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The first A350-1000 was assembled in 2016 and had its first flight on 24 November 2016.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The aircraft was then delivered on 20 February 2018 to Qatar Airways, which had also been the launch operator of the -900. and entered the commercial service with a flight from Doha to London on 24 February 2018.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The 60.45 m (198.3 ft)-long A350-800 was designed to seat 276 passengers in a typical three-class configuration with a range of 15,270 kilometres (8,245 nmi; 9,488 mi) with an MTOW of 259 tonnes (571,000 lb).
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] In January 2010, Airbus opted to develop the -800 as a shrink of the baseline -900 to simplify development and increase its payload by 3 tonnes (6,600 lb) or its range by 460 kilometres (250 nmi; 290 mi), but this led to a fuel burn penalty of "a couple of percent", according to John Leahy.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The previously planned optimisation to the structure and landing gear was not beneficial enough against better commonality and maximum takeoff weight increase by 11t from 248t.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The −800's fuselage is 10 frames shorter (six forward and four aft of wing) than the −900 aircraft.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] It was designed to supplement the Airbus A330-200 long-range twin.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Airbus planned to decrease structural weight in the -800 as development continued, which should have been around airframe 20.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] While its backlog reached 182 in mid-2008, it diminished since 2010 as customers switched to the larger -900.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] After launching the Airbus A330neo at the 2014 Farnborough Airshow, Airbus dropped the A350-800, with its CEO Fabrice Brégier saying "I believe all of our customers will either convert to the A350-900 or the A330neo".
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] He later confirmed at a September 2014 press conference that development of the A350-800 had been "cancelled".
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] There were 16 orders left for the -800 since Yemenia switched to the -900 and Hawaiian Airlines moved to the A330neo in December 2014: eight for Aeroflot and eight for Asiana Airlines, both also having orders for the -900.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] In January 2017, Aeroflot and Airbus announced the cancellation of its -800 order, leaving Asiana Airlines as the only customer for the variant.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] After the negotiation between Airbus and Asiana Airlines, Asiana converted orders of eight A350-800s and one A350-1000 to nine A350-900s.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] In 2011, Airbus redesigned the A350-1000 with higher weights and a more powerful engine variant to provide more range for trans-Pacific operations.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] This boosted its appeal to Cathay Pacific and Singapore Airlines, who were committed to purchase 20 Boeing 777-9s, and to United Airlines, which was considering Boeing 777-300ERs to replace its 747-400s.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Emirates was disappointed with the changes and cancelled its order for 50 A350-900s and 20 A350-1000s, instead of changing the whole order to the larger variant.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Assembly of the first fuselage major components started in September 2015.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] In February 2016, final assembly started at the A350 Final Assembly Line in Toulouse.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Three flight test aircraft were planned, with entry into service scheduled for mid-2017.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The first aircraft completed its body join on 15 April 2016.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Its maiden flight took place on 24 November 2016.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Airbus then completed functional and reliability testing.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Type Certification was awarded by EASA on 21 November 2017, along FAA certification.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The first serial unit was on the final assembly line in early December.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] After its maiden flight on 7 December 2017, delivery to launch customer Qatar Airways slipped to early 2018.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The delay was due to issues with the business class seat installation.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] It was delivered on 20 February 2018 and entered commercial service on Qatar Airways' Doha to London Heathrow route on 24 February 2018.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Airbus has explored the possibility of a further stretch offering 45 more seats.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] This variant was to be a replacement for the 747-400, tentatively called the A350-8000, -2000 or -1100.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] At the June 2016 Airbus Innovation Days, chief commercial officer John Leahy was concerned about the size of a 400-seat market besides the Boeing 747-8 and the 777-9 and chief executive Fabrice Brégier feared such an aircraft could cannibalise demand for the -1000.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The potential 79 m-long (258 ft) aeroplane was competing against a hypothetical 777-10 for Singapore Airlines.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] At the 2017 Paris Air Show, the concept was shelved for lacking market appeal and in January 2018 Brégier focused on enhancing the A350-900/1000 to capture potential before 2022/2023, when it would be possible to stretch the A350 with a new engine generation.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The wing twist is being changed for the wider, optimised spanload pressure distribution, and will be used for the Singapore Airlines A350-900ULR in 2018 before spreading to other variants.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] On 26 June 2018, Iberia was the first to receive the upgraded -900, with a 280 t (620,000 lb) MTOW version for an 8,200 nmi (15,200 km; 9,400 mi) range with 325 passengers in three classes.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] This eventually became a standard package for all the A350-900 airframes starting from **MSN 216**.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] By April 2019, Airbus was testing a hybrid laminar flow control (HLFC) on the leading edge of an A350 prototype vertical stabiliser, with passive suction similar to the boundary layer control on the Boeing 787-9 tail, but unlike the natural laminar flow BLADE, within the same EU Clean Sky programme.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Starting with **MSN 316**, every A350-900 and A350-1000 produced had the side slip angle (SSA) probe removed after a software update to prove these sensors are not needed anymore for redundancy.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] There was also a new light-emitting diode (LED) lighting package installed, replacing the old high-intensity discharge (HID) lamps; these new light units have a longer life cycle, improving reliability performance.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] In June 2019, Airbus delivered the first A350 equipped with the improvement package to Singapore Airlines (9V-SHH).
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] On 30 September 2022, an improved new production standard (**NPS**) was announced, it will apply to A359/A35K airframes starting from **MSN 579**, which is an A350-900 airframe that was delivered to Iberia.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The NPS includes a 1.2 t (2,600 lb) weight reduction and a 3 t (6,600 lb) MTOW increase, along with a wider interior cabin to offer 30 additional seats.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] It offers the customers with a new weight variant **WV020** for the 283 t MTOW.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The interior changes include moving the cockpit wall forward, moving the aft pressure bulkhead one frame further aft and resculpting the sidewalls to allow ten-across 17 in (430 mm) seats.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] There are also improvements to the aircraft's take off performance by introducing software evolutions which regulate the slat and flap positions, and has also implemented a faster landing gear retraction cycle – conferring greater obstacle clearance and reduced aerodynamic drag.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] By November 2018, Airbus was hiring in Toulouse and Madrid to develop a re-engined A350neo.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Although its launch is not guaranteed, it would be delivered in the mid-2020s, after the A321XLR and a stretched A320neo "plus", potentially competing with the Boeing New Midsize Airplane.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Service entry would be determined by ultra-high bypass ratio engine developments pursued by Pratt & Whitney, testing its Geared Turbofan upgrade; Safran Aircraft Engines, ground testing a demonstrator from 2021; and Rolls-Royce, targeting a 2025 Ultrafan service entry.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The production target is a monthly rate of 20 A350neos, up from 10.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] In November 2019, General Electric was offering an advanced GEnx-1 variant with a bleed air system and improvements from the GE9X, developed for the delayed Boeing 777X, to power a proposed A350neo from the mid-2020s.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] In 2021, Rolls Royce signed an exclusive deal to supply A350-900 engines until 2030, following previous similar commitments for the A350-1000.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Airbus expected 10% lower airframe maintenance compared with the original A350 design and 14% lower empty seat weight than the Boeing 777.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Design freeze for the A350-900 was achieved in December 2008.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The A350's competitor, the Boeing 787, is 50% composites, 20% aluminium, 15% titanium, 10% steel, and 5% other.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The A350 features a new composite fuselage with a constant width from door 1 to door 4, unlike previous Airbus aircraft, to provide maximum usable volume.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The double-lobe (ovoid) fuselage cross-section has a maximum outer diameter of 5.97 m (19.6 ft), compared to 5.64 m (18.5 ft) for the A330/A340.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The cabin's internal width is 5.61 m (18.4 ft) at armrest level compared to 5.49 m (18.0 ft) in the Boeing 787 and 5.87 m (19.3 ft) in the Boeing 777.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] It allows for an eight-across 2–4–2 arrangement in a premium economy layout, with the seats being 49.5 cm (19.5 in) wide between 5 cm (2.0 in) wide arm rests.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Airbus states that the seat will be 1.3 cm (0.5 in) wider than a 787 seat in the equivalent configuration.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] In the nine-across, 3–3–3 standard economy layout, the A350 seat will be 45 cm (18 in) wide, 1.27 cm (0.5 in) wider than a seat in the equivalent layout in the 787, and 3.9 cm (1.5 in) wider than a seat in the equivalent A330 layout.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The current 777 and future derivatives have 1.27 cm (0.5 in) greater seat width than the A350 in a nine-across configuration.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The 10-across seating on the A350 is similar to a 9-across configuration on the A330, with a seat width of 41.65 cm (16.4 in).
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Overall, the A350 gives passengers more headroom, larger overhead storage space, and wider panoramic windows than current Airbus models.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The A350 nose section has a configuration derived from the A380 with a forward-mounted nosegear bay and a six-panel flightdeck windscreen.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] This differs substantially from the four-window arrangement in the original A350 XWB design.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The new nose, made of aluminium, improves aerodynamics and enables overhead crew rest areas to be installed further forward and eliminate any encroachment in the passenger cabin.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The new windscreen has been revised to improve vision by reducing the width of the centre post.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The upper shell radius of the nose section has been increased.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The Airbus A350 initially featured manual window shades.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] In 2020, Airbus announced that dimmable windows, similar to those on the Boeing 787, would be offered as an option.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] These windows are designed to darken or lighten more efficiently, providing greater control over light levels while maintaining an outside view.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Starlux Airlines became the first carrier to receive A350s equipped with dimmable windows across all cabins, while Japan Airlines offers this feature exclusively in premium economy and higher-class cabins, retaining manual shades for economy passengers.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The A350 features new composite wings with a wingspan that is common to the proposed variants.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Its 64.75 m (212.4 ft) wingspan stays within the same ICAO Aerodrome Reference Code E 65 m limit as the A330/A340 and the Boeing 777.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The A350's wing has a 31.9° sweep angle for a Mach 0.85 cruise speed and has a maximum operating speed of Mach 0.89.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] This is between the 436.8 m2 (4,702 sq ft) wing of the current Boeing 777-200LR/300ER and the 466.8 m2 (5,025 sq ft) wing of the in-development Boeing 777X.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] However, Boeing and Airbus do not use the same measurement.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The A350-1000 wing is 22.3 m2 (240 ft2) larger through a 30 cm (12 in) extension to the inboard sections of the fixed trailing edge.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] A new trailing-edge high-lift device has been adopted with an advanced dropped-hinge flap similar to that of the A380, which permits the gap between the trailing edge and the flap to be closed with the spoiler.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The manufacturer has extensively used computational fluid dynamics and also carried out more than 4,000 hours of low- and high-speed windtunnel testing to refine the aerodynamic design.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The final configuration of wing and winglet was achieved for the "Maturity Gate 5" on 17 December 2008.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The wingtip device curves upwards over the final 4.4 m (14 ft).
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The wings are produced in the new £400 million (US$641M), 46,000 m2 (500,000 sq ft) North Factory at Airbus Broughton, employing 650 workers, in a specialist facility constructed with £29M of support from the Welsh Government.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Airbus adopted a new philosophy for the attachment of the A350's main undercarriage as part of the switch to a composite wing structure.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Each main undercarriage leg is attached to the rear wing spar forward and to a gear beam aft, which itself is attached to the wing and the fuselage.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] To help reduce the loads further into the wing, a double side-stay configuration has been adopted.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] This solution resembles the design of the Vickers VC10.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Airbus devised a three-pronged main undercarriage design philosophy encompassing both four- and six-wheel bogies to stay within pavement loading limits.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The A350-900 has four-wheel bogies in a 4.1 m (13 ft) long bay.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The higher weight variant, the A350-1000 uses a six-wheel bogie, with a 4.7 m (15 ft) undercarriage bay.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] French-based Messier-Dowty provides the main undercarriage for the -900 variant, with titanium forgings from Kobelco, and UTC Aerospace Systems supplies the -1000 variant.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The nose gear is supplied by Liebherr Aerospace.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Honeywell supplies its 1,300-kilowatt (1,700-horsepower) HGT1700 auxiliary power unit with 10% greater power density than the TPE331 from which it is developed, and the air management system: the bleed air, environmental control, cabin pressure control and supplemental cooling systems.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Airbus says that the new design provides a better cabin atmosphere with 20% humidity, a typical cabin altitude at or below 6,000 ft (1,800 m) and an airflow management system that adapts cabin airflow to passenger load with draught-free air circulation.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The ram air turbine, with a nominal power of 50 kilovolt-amperes, is supplied by Hamilton Sundstrand and located in the lower surface of the fuselage.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] In light of the 787 Dreamliner battery problems, in February 2013 Airbus decided to revert from lithium-ion to the proven nickel-cadmium technology although the flight test programme will continue with the lithium-ion battery systems.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] 24 was delivered with 80 kg (176 lb) lighter Saft Li-ion batteries and in June 2017, fifty A350s were flying with them and benefiting from a two-year maintenance schedule instead of NiCd's 4–6 months.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Parker Hannifin supplies the complete fuel package: inerting system, fuel measurement and management systems, mechanical equipment and fuel pumps.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The fuel tank inerting system features air-separation modules to generate nitrogen-enriched air to reduce the flammability of fuel vapour in the tanks.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Parker also provides hydraulic power generation and distribution system: reservoirs, manifolds, accumulators, thermal control, isolation, software and new engine- and electric motor-driven pump designs.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Parker estimates the contracts will generate more than US$2 billion in revenues over the life of the programme.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The revised design of the A350 XWB's glass cockpit dropped the A380-sized display and adopted 38 cm (15 in) liquid-crystal display screens.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Airbus says the cockpit design allows for future advances in navigation technology to be placed on the displays plus gives flexibility and capacity to upload new software and to combine data from multiple sources and sensors for flight management and aircraft systems control.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] An optional head-up display is also present in the cockpit.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Avionics are a further development of the integrated modular avionics (IMA) concept found on the A380.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The A350's IMA will manage up to 40 functions (versus 23 functions for the A380) such as undercarriage, fuel, pneumatics, cabin environmental systems, and fire detection.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Airbus stated that the benefits includes reduced maintenance and lower weight because as the IMA replaces multiple processors and LRUs with around 50% fewer standard computer modules known as line-replaceable modules.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The IMA runs on a 100 Mbit/s network based on the Avionics Full-Duplex Switched Ethernet standard, as employed in the A380, in place of the architecture used on the A330/A340.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] In 2005, GE was the launch engine of the original A350, aiming for 2010 deliveries, while Rolls-Royce offered its Trent 1700.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] For the updated A350 XWB, GE offered a 87,000 lbf (390 kN) GEnx-3A87 for the A350-800/900, but not a higher thrust version needed for the A350-1000, which competes with the longer range 777 powered exclusively with the GE90-115B.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] In December 2006, Rolls-Royce was selected for the A350 XWB launch engine.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The Rolls-Royce Trent XWB features a 300 cm (118 in) diameter fan and the design is based on the advanced developments of the Airbus A380 Trent 900 and the Boeing 787 Trent 1000.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The higher-thrust version will have some modifications to the fan module—it will be the same diameter but will run slightly faster and have a new fan blade design—and run at increased temperatures allowed by new materials technologies from Rolls-Royce's research.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The Trent XWB may also benefit from the next-generation reduced acoustic mode scattering engine duct system (RAMSES), an acoustic quieting engine nacelle intake, and a carry-on design of the Airbus's "zero splice" intake liner developed for the A380.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] A "hot and high" rating option for Middle Eastern customers Qatar Airways, Emirates, and Etihad Airways keep its thrust available at higher temperatures and altitudes.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Airbus aimed to certify the A350 with 350-minute ETOPS capability on entry into service; although Airbus achieved a 370-minute ETOPS rating on 15 October 2014, which covers 99.7% of the Earth's surface.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] There are plans to extend this to 420 minutes in the future.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Engine thrust-reversers and nacelles are supplied by US-based Collins Aerospace (formerly UTC Aerospace Systems).
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] One year after introduction, the A350 fleet had accumulated 3,000 flight cycles and around 16,000 block hours.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Finnair was operating the A350 at very high rates: 15 flight hours per day for Beijing, 18 hours for Shanghai, and more than 20 hours for Bangkok.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] This may have accelerated the retirement of the Airbus A340.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] In service, problems occurred in three areas.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The onboard maintenance, repair, overhaul network needed software improvements.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Airbus issued service bulletins regarding onboard equipment and removed galley inserts (coffee makers, toaster ovens) because of leaks.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Airbus had to address spurious overheating warnings in the bleed air system by retrofitting an original connector with a gold-plated connector.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Airbus targeted a 98.5% dependability by the end of 2016 and to match the mature A330 in terms of reliability by early 2019.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] By the end of May 2016, the A350 fleet had flown 55,200 hours over 9,400 cycles at a 97.8% operational reliability on three months.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The longest operated sector was Qatar Airways' Adelaide–Doha at 13.8 hours for 6,120 nmi (11,334 km; 7,043 mi).
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The average flight was 6.8 hours, with the longest average being 9.6 hours by TAM Airlines and the shortest being 2.1 hours by Cathay Pacific's.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] It is able to seat from 253 seats for Singapore Airlines to 348 seats for TAM Airlines, with a 30 to 46 seat business class and a 211 to 318 seat economy class, often including a premium economy.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] A total of 49 A350s were delivered to customers in 2016.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] It was also planned that the monthly rate would grow to 10 by the end of 2018, which was eventually achieved in 2019 when Airbus delivered 112 aircraft over a period of 11 months.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] In January 2017, two years after introduction, 62 aircraft were in service with 10 airlines.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] They had accumulated 25,000 flights over 154,000 hours with an average daily utilisation of 12.5 hours, and transported six million passengers with a 98.7% operational reliability.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Zodiac Aerospace encountered production difficulties with business class seats in their Texas and California factories.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] After a year, Cathay Pacific experienced cosmetic quality issues and upgraded or replaced the seats for the earliest cabins.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] In 2017, average test flights before delivery decreased to 4.1 from 12 in 2014, with an average delay down to 25 days from 68.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] In June 2017 after 30 months in commercial operation, 80 A350s were in service with 12 operators, the largest being Qatar Airways with 17 and 13 each at Cathay Pacific and Singapore Airlines (SIA).
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The fleet average block time (time between pushback and destination gate arrival) was 7.2 hours with 53% below 3,000 nmi (5,556 km; 3,452 mi), 16% over 5,000 nmi (9,260 km; 5,754 mi), and 31% in between.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] LATAM Airlines had the longest average sector at 10.7 hours, and Asiana had the shortest at 3.8 hours.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Singapore Airlines operated the longest leg, Singapore to San Francisco 7,340 nmi (13,594 km; 8,447 mi), and the shortest leg, Singapore to Kuala Lumpur 160 nmi (296 km; 184 mi).
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Seating varied from 253 for Singapore Airlines to 389 for Air Caraïbes, with most between 280 and 320.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] As of February 2018, 142 A350-900s had been delivered, and were in operation with a dispatch reliability of 99.3%.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] As of November 2019, 33 operators had received 331 aircraft from 959 orders, and 2.6 million hours have been flown.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] As of October 2025, the global A350 fleet of 682 aircraft had completed more than 2,000,000 flights on more than 1,365 routes, and had carried more than 530 million passengers since its entry into service; the fleet had 99.2% operational reliability in the last 3 months.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] In August 2021, as several A350s were sent in to be repainted in a scheme advertising the 2022 FIFA World Cup (played in Qatar), Qatar Airways discovered that their paint was unusually degraded.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The airline grounded its A350s until the root cause could be determined, and would not accept new aircraft deliveries until the problem could be solved.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The European civil aviation regulator, EASA, found that paint degradation did not affect the aircraft structure or introduce "other risks".
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The Qatari civil aviation regulator was the only one that agreed with the airline that it was an airworthiness issue.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] In November 2021, Reuters found that Finnair, Cathay Pacific, Etihad, Lufthansa and Air France had also complained of paint damage as early as 2016.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Singapore Airlines had not detected such problems with its fleet.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] On 20 December 2021, Airbus received a formal legal claim in the English courts filed by Qatar Airways.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Qatar Airways alleged that the surface flaws cause the risk of fuel tank ignition due to the degradation in lightning protection over the fuel tanks in the wings.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Qatar Airways claimed it was owed US$200,000 per day in compensation for each grounded aircraft.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Meanwhile, according to a Flight International editorial, Airbus's decision to cancel Qatar's outstanding orders indicated that it was certain of its case.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] The court hearing was originally scheduled for summer 2023.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] Both Airbus and Qatar Airways agreed to settle the dispute on 1 February 2023.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p01] While the settlement was confidential, Flight International believed that Airbus achieved a more favourable outcome, opining that there was no major impact to Airbus's finances, the A350's reputation remained intact and Qatar's A321neos would nevertheless be delivered.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] The three main variants of the A350 were launched in 2006, with entry into service planned for 2013.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] At the 2011 Paris Air Show, Airbus postponed the entry into service of the A350-1000 by two years to mid-2017.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] In July 2012, the A350's entry into service was delayed to the second half of 2014, before the -900 began service on 15 January 2015.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] In October 2012, the -800 was due to enter service in mid-2016, but its development was cancelled in September 2014 in favour of the reengined Airbus A330neo.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] The A350 is also offered as the ACJ350 corporate jet by Airbus Corporate Jets (ACJ), offering a 20,000 km; 12,400 mi (10,800 nmi) range for 25 passengers for the -900 derivative.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] The A350-900 (ICAO code: A359) is the first A350 model; it has a MTOW of 283 tonnes (624,000 lb) when powered by the Trent XWB-84 or 255 tonnes (562,000 lb) when powered by the Trent XWB-75, typically seats 325 passengers, and has a range of 8,500 nmi (15,700 km; 9,800 mi).
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] Airbus says that per seat, the Boeing 777-200ER should have a 16% heavier manufacturer's empty weight, a 30% higher block fuel consumption, and 25% higher cash operating costs than the A350-900.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] The −900 is designed to compete with the Boeing 777-200LR and 787-10, while replacing the Airbus A340-500 and Boeing 777-200ER.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] A proposed A350−900R extended-range variant was to feature the higher engine thrust, strengthened structure, and landing gear of the 308 tonnes (679,000 lb) MTOW -1000 to give a further 800 nmi (1,500 km; 920 mi) range.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] Philippine Airlines (PAL) announced in 2016 that it will replace its A340-300 with an A350-900HGW ("high-gross weight") variant available from 2017 ,which it received in July 2018.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] It enabled non-stop Manila-New York City flights without payload limitations in either direction, a 7,404 nmi (13,712 km; 8,520 mi) flight.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] This will enable an 8,100 nmi (15,000 km; 9,300 mi) range with 325 seats in a three-class layout.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] In early November 2017, Emirates committed to purchase 40 Boeing 787-10 aircraft before Airbus presented an updated A350-900 layout with the rear pressure bulkhead pushed back by 2.5 ft (76 cm).
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] After Emirates' Tim Clark was shown a ten-across economy cabin and galley changes, he said the -900 is "more marketable" as a result.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] By 2018, a 2014 build was valued $108M falling to $74.5M by 2022 while a new build was valued for $148M, a 6+12 year check cost $3M and an engine overhaul $4–6.5M.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] The MTOW is increased by 5 tonnes (11,000 lb) from the previously certified 275 tonnes (606,000 lb) variant.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] Because of the A350-900's fuel consumption of 5.8 tonnes (13,000 lb) per hour, it needs an additional 24 tonnes (53,000 lb) of fuel to fly 19 hours instead of the standard 15 hours: the increased MTOW and lower payloads will enable the larger fuel capacity.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] Non-stop flights could last more than 20 hours.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] The first −900ULR was rolled out without its engines in February 2018 for ground testing.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] Flight-tests after engine installation checked the larger fuel capacity and measured the performance improvements from the extended winglets.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] It made its first flight on 23 April 2018.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] There are no addition structural changes fitted to the A350-900ULR, therefore it retains the same type certificate and model name as the baseline A350-941.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] The larger fuel capacity is enabled by integrating a modified fuel system to make use of the extra spaces in the centre wing box, no auxiliary fuel tanks are fitted.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] Also the front cargo hold is disabled due to operational limits but can be reactivated depending on customer needs.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] Singapore Airlines, the launch customer, uses its seven -900ULR aircraft on non-stop flights between Singapore and New York City and cities on the U.S. west coast.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] Singapore Airlines' seating is to range from 170 in largely business class seating up to over 250 in mixed seating.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] The airline received its first -900ULR on 23 September 2018, with 67 business class seats and 94 premium economy seats.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] On 12 October 2018, it landed the world's then-longest flight at Newark Liberty International Airport from Singapore Changi after 17 hours and 52 minutes, covering 16,561 kilometres (8,942 nmi; 10,291 mi) for a 15,353 kilometres (8,290 nmi; 9,540 mi) orthodromic distance.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] It burned 101.4 t (224,000 lb) of fuel to cover the route in 17 h 22 min: an average of 5.8 tonnes per hour (1.6 kg/s).
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] As of 2022, the A350-900ULR is used on the longest flight in the world, Singapore Airlines Flights 23 and 24 from Singapore to New York JFK.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] At the 2015 Dubai Air Show, John Leahy noted the demand of the Persian Gulf airlines for this variant.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] In February 2018, Qatar Airways stated its preference for the larger -1000, having no need for the extra range of the -900ULR.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] Compared to the standard -900, the -900ULR additional value is likely around $2 million.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] Airbus Corporate Jet version of the A350, the ACJ350, is derived from the A350-900ULR.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] As a result of the increased fuel capacity from the -900ULR, the ACJ350 has a maximum range of 20,550 km (11,100 nmi; 12,770 mi).
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] The German Air Force is to be the first to receive the ACJ350, having ordered three aircraft which will replace its two A340-300s.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] After the Boeing 787-10 launch at the 2013 Paris Air Show, Airbus discussed with airlines a possible A350-900 Regional with a reduced MTOW of 250 t (550,000 lb).
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] Engine thrust would have been reduced to 70,000–75,000 lbf (310–330 kN) from the standard 85,000 lbf (380 kN) and the variant would have been optimised for routes up to 6,800 nmi (12,600 km; 7,800 mi) with seating for up to 360 passengers in a single-class layout.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] The A350 Regional was expected to be ordered by Etihad Airways and Singapore Airlines.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] Since 2013, there has been no further announcement about this variant.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] Singapore Airlines selected an A350-900 version for medium-haul use, and Japan Airlines took delivery of a 369-seat A350-900 with a 217 t (478,000 lb) MTOW (WV018) for its domestic flight network.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] The A350-1000 (ICAO code: A35K) is the largest variant of the A350 family at just under 74 metres (243 ft) in length.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] It seats 369 passengers in a typical two-class layout with a range of 9,000 nmi (17,000 km; 10,000 mi).
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] With a 9-across configuration, it is designed to replace the A340-600 and compete with the Boeing 777-300ER and 777-8.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] Airbus estimates a 366-seat -1000 should have a 35 tonnes (77,000 lb) lighter operating empty weight than a 398-seat 777-9, a 15% lower trip cost, a 7% lower seat cost, and a 400 nmi (740 km; 460 mi) greater range.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] Compared to a Boeing 777-300ER with 360 seats, Airbus claims a 25% fuel burn per seat advantage for an A350-1000 with 369 seats.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] The 7 m (23 ft) extension seats 40 more passengers with 40% more premium area.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] The -1000 can match the 40 more seats of the 777-9 with a 10-across seating configuration but diminished comfort.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] The A350-1000 has an 11-frame stretch over the −900 and a slightly larger wing than the −800/900 models with trailing-edge extension increasing its area by 4%.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] This will extend the high-lift devices and the ailerons, making the chord bigger by around 400 mm (16 in), optimising flap lift performance as well as cruise performance.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] The main landing gear is a 6-wheel bogie instead of a 4-wheel bogie, put in a one frame longer bay.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] The Rolls-Royce Trent XWB engine's thrust is augmented to 97,000 lbf (430 kN).
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] These and other engineering upgrades are necessary so that the −1000 model maintains range.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] It features an automatic emergency descent function to around 10,000 ft (3,000 m) and notifies air traffic control if the crew fails to respond to an alert, indicating possible incapacitation from depressurisation.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] The avionics software adaptation is activated by a push and pull button to avoid mistakes and could be retrofitted in the smaller -900.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] All performance targets have been met or exceeded, and it remains within its weight specification, unlike early −900s.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] Its 316 t MTOW appeared on 29 May 2018 update of its type certificate data sheet.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] A further MTOW increase by 3 t (6,600 lb), to a total of 319 t (703,000 lb) was under study to be available from 2020 and could have been a response to Qantas' Project Sunrise.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] In November 2019, maximum accommodation increased to 480 seats from 440 through the installation of new "Type-A+" exits, with a dual-lane evacuation slide.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] On 17 December 2021, French Bee took delivery of the first A350-1000 in this 480-seat configuration, leased by Air Lease Corporation and to be operated from Paris to Réunion, with 40 premium and 440 economy seats.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] In October 2023, the variant's MTOW was raised again to 322 t (710,000 lb).
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] In December 2019, Qantas tentatively chose the A350-1000 to operate their Project Sunrise routes, before a final decision in March 2020 for up to 12 aircraft.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] Initial speculation suggested that the variant might be marketed as the A350-1000ULR.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] However, the -1000 is not expected to share the -900ULR's larger fuel tanks and other fuel system modifications, and Airbus had stopped short of describing the largest MTOW variant as a ULR model, despite the 8,700 nmi (16,100 km; 10,000 mi) range.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] After a delay due to the COVID-19 pandemic, the decision was confirmed on 2 May 2022, when Qantas placed a formal order for 12 Airbus A350-1000 aircraft for Project Sunrise flights to originally start in 2025.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] With Airbus integrating the tank into the A350-1000 for flight testing in early 2025 for delivery to the group in mid-2026.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] On 6 November 2025, Airbus and Qantas released a set of pictures of the upcoming first ultra long range A350-1000 variant (MSN 707) with a confirmed marketing name as A350-1000ULR being displayed on the aircraft.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] An A350-900 freighter was first mentioned in 2007, offering a similar capacity to the McDonnell Douglas MD-11F with a range of 9,250 km (5,000 nmi; 5,750 mi), to be developed after the passenger version.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] In early 2020, Airbus was proposing an A350F before a potential launch.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] The proposed freighter would be slightly longer than the A350-900 and Airbus would need 50 orders to launch the $2–3 billion programme.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] In July 2021, the Airbus board approved the freighter development.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] As of 2021, it is based on the -1000 version for a payload over 90 tonnes, and entry into service targeted for 2025.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] The A350F, also referred to by Airbus as the A350-1000F, would keep the 319-tonne MTOW previously announced for the passenger A350-1000 on a shortened fuselage, but the proposed design remains 6.9 m (23 ft) longer than the Boeing 777F with 10% larger freight volume at 695 m3 (24,500 cu ft).
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] With a main deck cargo door behind the wing and reinforced main deck aluminium floor beams, its 111 t (245,000 lb) payload is higher than the 103.7 t (229,000 lb) of the 777F, while its empty weight is 30 tonnes (66,000 lb) lighter than the A350-1000, 20 tonnes (44,000 lb) lighter than the 777F.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] The 70.8 m (232 ft) long cargo variant should have a 4,700 nmi (8,700 km; 5,400 mi) range at 109 tonnes structural payload.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] At the November 2021 Dubai Air Show, US lessor Air Lease Corporation became the launch customer with an order for seven to be delivered around 2026, among other Airbus airliners.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] Air Lease Corporation cancelled its launch order in August 2025.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] The launch operator of the A350F was initially planned to be Singapore Airlines, which ordered seven aircraft at the 2022 Singapore Airshow with deliveries expected to begin in 2026.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] In February 2025, Airbus announced that entry-into-service would be delayed until 2027 due to supply chain issues, particularly with Spirit Aerosystems which supplies the central fuselage section.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] After Air Lease Corporation's order cancellation, CMA CGM Air Cargo claimed in August 2025 that it would be the launch operator.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] In March 2026, Atlas Air announced a firm order for 20 A350Fs, marking the first time in its history that it would operate non-Boeing aircraft.
[src:emergency-exit/a350-1000-p02] Below is a list of major differences between the A350 variants.
[src:emergency-exit/active-fire-protection] Manual fire suppression includes the use of a fire blanket, fire extinguisher, or a standpipe system.
[src:emergency-exit/active-fire-protection] A fire blanket is a sheet of fire retardant material that is designed to be placed over a fire to smother it out.
[src:emergency-exit/active-fire-protection] Small fire blankets are meant for inception stage fires.
[src:emergency-exit/active-fire-protection] They are normally made of fiberglass or Kevlar.
[src:emergency-exit/active-fire-protection] Larger ones can be found in laboratories and factories, and are designed to be wrapped around a person whose clothes have caught fire.
[src:emergency-exit/active-fire-protection] Fire extinguishers are devices that contain and discharge a substance that extinguishes or puts out a fire.
[src:emergency-exit/active-fire-protection] These handheld devices come in a huge range of sizes, but the most common are portable fire extinguishers, typically weighing up to 15 kg in total.
[src:emergency-exit/active-fire-protection] These can be easily handled and operated by one person and placement can either be wall-mounted, on a fire extinguisher trolley or housed inside a cabinet.
[src:emergency-exit/active-fire-protection] Fire extinguishers are one of the most common manual fire suppression devices and are required in all commercial buildings and vehicles.
[src:emergency-exit/active-fire-protection] Fire extinguishers can be used with little to no training and are meant for small incipient stage fires.
[src:emergency-exit/active-fire-protection] The most common extinguisher is the ABC extinguisher and are found in most offices and homes.
[src:emergency-exit/active-fire-protection] It can be used on normal fires, liquid fires, and electrical fires.
[src:emergency-exit/active-fire-protection] There are also special extinguishers for kitchen fires and for use on burning metals, those being Class K and Class D respectively.
[src:emergency-exit/active-fire-protection] Standpipes are installed in most large, multistory buildings.
[src:emergency-exit/active-fire-protection] There are two types of standpipes: dry and wet.
[src:emergency-exit/active-fire-protection] Most standpipes are dry systems and cannot be used by the public.
[src:emergency-exit/active-fire-protection] Dry systems require a fire engine to pump water into the system.
[src:emergency-exit/active-fire-protection] Most dry systems do not have pre-connected hoses and require firefighters to bring in the hose.
[src:emergency-exit/active-fire-protection] In wet systems, there is always water in the pipes and they can be used by anyone.
[src:emergency-exit/active-fire-protection] Wet systems will have hoses so building occupants can try and extinguish fires.
[src:emergency-exit/active-fire-protection] Wet systems are becoming less common with the increase in number of sprinkler systems being installed.
[src:emergency-exit/active-fire-protection] In some systems, firefighters have the option of pumping a Fire Department Connection (FDC) which will increase the water pressure at a standpipe in the event of a fire pump failure or loss of pressure.
[src:emergency-exit/active-fire-protection] Typically, these systems pressurize the sprinkler system or the standpipe but not both at the same time.
[src:emergency-exit/active-fire-protection] Automatic control means are any form of suppression that requires no human intervention these can include a fire sprinkler system, a gaseous clean agent, or automatic foam suppression system.
[src:emergency-exit/active-fire-protection] Most automatic suppression systems would be found in large commercial kitchens or other high-risk areas.
[src:emergency-exit/active-fire-protection] Fire sprinkler systems are installed in all types of buildings, commercial and residential.
[src:emergency-exit/active-fire-protection] They are usually located at ceiling level and are connected to a reliable water source, most commonly municipal water supply.
[src:emergency-exit/active-fire-protection] A typical automatic sprinkler system operates when heat at the site of a fire causes a fusible link or glass component in the sprinkler head to fail, thereby releasing the water from the sprinkler head.
[src:emergency-exit/active-fire-protection] This means that only the sprinkler heads at the fire location actuate – not all the sprinklers on a floor or in a building.
[src:emergency-exit/active-fire-protection] However, certain systems, such as deluge systems, do spray water from all heads in the same zone upon actuation.
[src:emergency-exit/active-fire-protection] Sprinkler systems help to reduce the growth of a fire, thereby increasing life safety and limiting structural damage.
[src:emergency-exit/active-fire-protection] Gaseous clean agents are installed to result in less fire and water damage than sprinklers, such as in computer rooms.
[src:emergency-exit/active-fire-protection] The system works by flooding an area with a gas which interferes with the fire tetrahedron.
[src:emergency-exit/active-fire-protection] These systems are often found in areas where people are not going to be present when the system is activated such as datacenters, cooling systems, and other industrial applications.
[src:emergency-exit/active-fire-protection] Activating a gaseous clean agent system when people are present can cause injury or death, and are usually equipped with an audible notification system to warn any potential occupants to evacuate the area.
[src:emergency-exit/active-fire-protection] Automatic foam suppression systems come in three main forms low expansion, medium expansion, and high expansion.
[src:emergency-exit/active-fire-protection] Low expansion foam expands less than 20 times its original size.
[src:emergency-exit/active-fire-protection] These systems can be installed in a variety of places but are commonly found in places where hydrocarbons are stored.
[src:emergency-exit/active-fire-protection] Low expansion foam systems when using film forming work by making a blanket of foam over the burning liquid to both cool it down and suppress the vapors.
[src:emergency-exit/active-fire-protection] Medium expansion foam expands between 20 and 200 times its original size.
[src:emergency-exit/active-fire-protection] These can be installed in outdoor settings like transfer stations or for use in open pits.
[src:emergency-exit/active-fire-protection] Medium foam is used outdoors because it is denser than high expansion and will not blow away as easily.
[src:emergency-exit/active-fire-protection] It works by covering what is on fire in a thick blanket of foam to smother it and suppress vapors.
[src:emergency-exit/active-fire-protection] High expansion foam expands between 200 and 1000 times its original size.
[src:emergency-exit/active-fire-protection] These systems are commonly installed in large volume areas like airplane hangars, mine shafts, and ship holds.
[src:emergency-exit/active-fire-protection] These systems are normally installed inside and make a very light foam.
[src:emergency-exit/active-fire-protection] They extinguish the fire by rapid smothering and cooling.
[src:emergency-exit/active-fire-protection] Its rapid rate of expansion enables it to fill large areas with foam rapidly.
[src:emergency-exit/active-fire-protection] When used on LNG tanks they provide an added insulation layer that helps reduce the vapor rate.
[src:emergency-exit/active-fire-protection] Nozzles that are powered by electrical energy that is generated and supplied by fire detection and control devices and are typically closed.
[src:emergency-exit/active-fire-protection] ILDFA uses a dual approach, combining a water-based fire suppression system in conjunction with a hollow, perforated flooring system to drain and remove spilled flammable liquid.
[src:emergency-exit/active-fire-protection] This approach reduces the risk of pool fires inside infrastructure by diverting any leaked fuel away from potential ignition sources or by extinguishing any flammable liquid fire by depriving it of oxygen once it is removed.
[src:emergency-exit/active-fire-protection] Fire detection works using smoke or heat sensors.
[src:emergency-exit/active-fire-protection] These systems are very effective tool at alerting people in the immediate vicinity of where the fire is detected but building regulations require an integrated fire detection system.
[src:emergency-exit/active-fire-protection] These system not only alerts people throughout the building by triggering the fire alarm but it can also summon emergency services.
[src:emergency-exit/active-fire-protection] There are two types of systems available – addressable and conventional.
[src:emergency-exit/active-fire-protection] Addressable systems monitor the specific location of each device (e.g. smoke detector, call point or sounder).
[src:emergency-exit/active-fire-protection] It means in the event of a fire or other emergency you know exactly where the problem is.
[src:emergency-exit/active-fire-protection] This saves precious time and helps the emergency services prevent the loss of life and serious damage.
[src:emergency-exit/active-fire-protection] Conventional systems can only determine the problem is in a general area and thus are more suited for small sites.
[src:emergency-exit/active-fire-protection] When the fire detection system is activated it can also send an alert to the local fire department, broadcast a prerecorded warning message and unlock the buildings access control system.
[src:emergency-exit/active-fire-protection] Hypoxic air fire prevention systems, also known as oxygen reduction systems are new automatic fire prevention systems that permanently reduce the oxygen concentration inside the protected volumes so that ignition or fire spreading cannot occur.
[src:emergency-exit/active-fire-protection] Unlike traditional fire suppression systems that usually extinguish fire after it is detected, hypoxic air is able to prevent fires.
[src:emergency-exit/active-fire-protection] At lower altitudes hypoxic air is safe to breathe for healthy individuals.
[src:emergency-exit/active-fire-protection] All AFP systems are required to be installed and maintained in accordance with strict guidelines in order to maintain compliance with the local building code and the fire code.
[src:emergency-exit/active-fire-protection] AFP works alongside modern architectural designs and construction materials and fire safety education to prevent, retard, and suppress structural fires.
[src:emergency-exit/area-of-refuge] An **area of refuge** or **safe room** is a place in a building designed to hold occupants during a fire or other emergency when evacuation may not be safe or possible.
[src:emergency-exit/area-of-refuge] Occupants can wait there until rescued or relieved by firefighters.
[src:emergency-exit/area-of-refuge] In some instances, an area of refuge or refuge area may refer to a designated space in a multi-unit residential building that can provide relief from unsafe or uncomfortable conditions in individual units.
[src:emergency-exit/area-of-refuge] An area of refuge is typically supplied with a steady supply of fresh or filtered outside air.
[src:emergency-exit/area-of-refuge] A two way communication system is provided on each floor above or below the main floor.
[src:emergency-exit/area-of-refuge] A call box is required in each area of refuge, which can call into a central location called a base station.
[src:emergency-exit/area-of-refuge] If the station is not attended 24 hours a day, the call must automatically call to an outside location and have two-way voice person to person communication capabilities.
[src:emergency-exit/area-of-refuge] Such locations are usually required to be bounded by fire-resistant walls and floors.
[src:emergency-exit/area-of-refuge] In the context of climate change, where older buildings may not be designed for changing climate conditions, refuge spaces are sometimes discussed in terms of providing communal areas in multi-unit buildings for when temperature and air quality is not safe or comfortable in individual units.
[src:emergency-exit/arthur-b-guise-medal] Guise Medal** was established in 1983 and has been awarded annually starting in 1985 by the Society of Fire Protection Engineers.
[src:emergency-exit/arthur-b-guise-medal] Named in memory of Arthur Guise, an engineer who developed dry chemicals as fire extinguishing agents, it recognizes eminent achievement in the advancement of the science and technology of fire protection engineering.
[src:emergency-exit/aspirating-smoke-detector] An **aspirating smoke detector** (**ASD**) is a system used in active fire protection, consisting of a central detection unit which draws air through a network of pipes to detect smoke.
[src:emergency-exit/aspirating-smoke-detector] The sampling chamber is based on a nephelometer that detects the presence of smoke particles suspended in air by detecting the light scattered by them in the chamber.
[src:emergency-exit/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASDs can typically detect smoke before it is visible to the naked eye.
[src:emergency-exit/aspirating-smoke-detector] In most cases aspirating smoke detectors require a fan unit to draw in a sample of air from the protected area through its network of pipes.
[src:emergency-exit/aspirating-smoke-detector] In 1970 the Australian Commonwealth Scientific and Industrial Research Organisation (CSIRO) used a nephelometer to carry out research into forest fires.
[src:emergency-exit/aspirating-smoke-detector] Subsequently, the Australian Postmaster-General's Department engaged the CSIRO to investigate technologies that could prevent service interruption due to fire.
[src:emergency-exit/aspirating-smoke-detector] After selecting a sample site to carry out research, the CSIRO suggested that the nephelometer should be used as the benchmark for the APO fire tests.
[src:emergency-exit/aspirating-smoke-detector] This was installed to monitor smoke levels within the return-air ducts of the mechanical ventilation system, utilising a chart-recorder output display.
[src:emergency-exit/aspirating-smoke-detector] At the conclusion of several weeks of testing, it was discovered that there no commercially available fire detection technology suitable for preventing damage to telephone equipment.
[src:emergency-exit/aspirating-smoke-detector] One technology that did show great promise however was the nephelometer itself.
[src:emergency-exit/aspirating-smoke-detector] In 1979, Xtralis, then IEI Pty Ltd., produced and sold an air sampling device they called VESDA (Very Early Smoke Detection Apparatus).
[src:emergency-exit/aspirating-smoke-detector] The company redesigned the detector in 1982 to provide the reliability, features, size and reduced cost for export markets.
[src:emergency-exit/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASD systems have gained popularity due to their ability to sense smoke long before a catastrophic incident.
[src:emergency-exit/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASD design corrects shortcomings of conventional smoke detectors by using a sampling pipe with multiple holes.
[src:emergency-exit/aspirating-smoke-detector] The air samples are captured and filtered, removing any contaminants or dust to avoid false alarms and then processed by a centralized, highly sensitive laser detection unit.
[src:emergency-exit/aspirating-smoke-detector] If smoke is detected, the systems alarm is triggered, and signals are then processed through centralized monitoring stations within a few seconds.
[src:emergency-exit/aspirating-smoke-detector] Unlike passive smoke detection systems, including spot detectors, ASD systems actively draw smoke to the detector through bore holes within a piping system that runs throughout the protected area.
[src:emergency-exit/aspirating-smoke-detector] Furthermore, ASD systems incorporate integrity monitoring to ensure an alert is raised at any time the ASD's ability to detect smoke is compromised.
[src:emergency-exit/aspirating-smoke-detector] This is not the case with passive devices that are generally only electrically monitored with no ability to determine if smoke can actually reach the detection element.
[src:emergency-exit/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASD systems incorporate more than one level of alarm.
[src:emergency-exit/aspirating-smoke-detector] This allows an ASD system to provide very early warning of an event, prompting investigation at the earliest smouldering stage of a fire when it is easily addressed.
[src:emergency-exit/aspirating-smoke-detector] Other alarm levels may be configured to provide fire alarm inputs to fire systems as well as releasing suppression systems.
[src:emergency-exit/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASD alarm sensitivities are configurable and can be programmed to levels ranging from thousands of times more sensitive than a conventional detector, to much less sensitive.
[src:emergency-exit/aspirating-smoke-detector] The detectors work best in non-volatile environments.
[src:emergency-exit/aspirating-smoke-detector] They can also be used in computer cabinets to alert users to the overheating of computer cables or individual computer components.
[src:emergency-exit/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASDs are suitable for environments where a highly sensitive rapid smoke detection capability is required.
[src:emergency-exit/aspirating-smoke-detector] This makes them suitable in clean rooms; areas which contain goods easily damaged by fire, such as tobacco, electronic rooms and highly flammable liquid and gases.
[src:emergency-exit/aspirating-smoke-detector] Often, normal point detectors will recognise the danger too late, as smoke often does not reach the ceiling quickly enough for a fire to be detected in a timely fashion.
[src:emergency-exit/aspirating-smoke-detector] As they can be easily hidden, pipe networks are suitable in environments where point detectors can be considered aesthetically displeasing, such as offices, apartments and hotel rooms.
[src:emergency-exit/aspirating-smoke-detector] This factor also makes them suitable in locations where point detectors can be easily tampered with, such as in correctional facilities.
[src:emergency-exit/aspirating-smoke-detector] Despite their high sensitivity ASDs can be used in dusty or dirty environments as long as correct design, installation and maintenance processes are followed.
[src:emergency-exit/aspirating-smoke-detector] Most ASD products can accommodate a broad range of environments and applications – from both confined and open spaces to the cleanest or dirtiest environment, including telecomm, control rooms, waste treatment, mining and more.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] An **emergency exit** (also known as a **fire exit**) is a special exit used during emergencies in a building or other structure such as fires.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] The combined use of regular and emergency exits allows for faster evacuation, and emergency exits provide alternative means of evacuation if regular exits are inaccessible.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] An emergency exit's path usually ends in an outward-opening door with a crash bar with exit signs pointing to it.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] It is usually a door to an area outside of the building, but may also lead to an adjoining, fire-isolated structure with clear exits of its own.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] A fire escape is a special kind of emergency exit consisting of stairs and/or extendable escape ladders mounted on the outside of a building.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] Local building codes or building regulations often dictate the number of fire exits required for a building of a given size, including the number of stairwells.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] For any buildings bigger than a private house, modern codes invariably specify at least two sets of stairs, completely isolated from each other so that if one becomes impassable due to smoke or flames, the other remains usable.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] The traditional way to satisfy this requirement was to construct two separate stairwell stacks, each occupying its own footprint within each floorplan.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] Each stairwell is internally configured into an arrangement often called a "U-return" or "return" design.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] The two stairwells may be constructed next to each other, separated by a fireproof partition, or optionally the two stairwells may be located at some distance from each other within the floorplan.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] The traditional arrangement has the advantage of being easily understood by building occupants and occasional visitors.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] Some architects save space while still meeting the exit requirement, by housing two stairwells in a "double helix" or "scissors stairs" configuration whereby two stairwells occupy the same floor footprint, but are intertwined while being separated by fireproof partitions along their entire run.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] However, this design deposits anybody descending the stack into alternating locations on each successive floor, and this can be very disorienting.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] Some building codes recommend using a color-coded stripe and signage to distinguish otherwise identical-looking stairwells from each other, and to make following a quick exit path easier.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] In older buildings that predate modern fire codes, and which lack space for a second stairwell, having intertwining stairs so close to each other may not allow firefighters going up and evacuees going down to use separate stairways.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] For example, Westfield Stratford City uses a scissors stairway configuration in its upper car park.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] This part of the building has eight storeys: LG, G, and 1 are part of the shopping centre; 2 has some offices and a storage area; CP1, CP2, CP3, and CP4 are a multi-storey car park.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] The floors are served by the main public lifts and escalators, and by 1 set of a double-helix stairway and lift per 1,000 square metres (11,000 sq ft), going into the service areas.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] The main public escalators do not count as fire exits, as the doors may be locked during less busy periods.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] The building has one fire exit per 4,000 square metres (43,000 sq ft) of floor space.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] Knowing the location of emergency exits in buildings can save lives.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] Some buildings, such as schools, have fire drills to practice using emergency exits.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] Many disasters could have been prevented if people had known where fire escapes were and if emergency exits had not been blocked.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] For example, in the September 11, 2001, attacks on the World Trade Center, some of the emergency exits inside the building were inaccessible, while others were locked.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] In the Stardust Disaster and the 2006 Moscow hospital fire, the emergency exits were locked and most windows barred shut.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] In the case of the Station Nightclub, the premises were over capacity the night fire broke out, the front exit was not designed well (right outside the door, the concrete approach split 90 degrees and a railing ran along the edge), and an emergency exit swung inward, not outward as code requires.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] In many countries, it is required that all new commercial buildings include well-marked emergency exits.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] Some older buildings must be retrofitted with fire escapes.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] In countries where emergency exits are not standard, or the standards are not enforced, fires will often result in a much greater loss of life.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] The UK Health and Safety (Safety Signs and Signals) Regulations 1996 define a fire safety sign as an illuminated sign or acoustic signal that provides information on escape routes and emergency exits.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] Well-designed emergency exit signs are necessary for emergency exits to be effective.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] Fire escape signs usually display the word "EXIT" or the equivalent word in the local language with large, well-lit, green letters, or the green pictorial "running-man" symbol developed and adopted in Japan around 1980 and introduced in 2003 by ISO 7010.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] Pictorial green "running-man" sign is mandatory in Japan, European Union, South Korea, Australia, New Zealand and Canada, and increasingly becoming common elsewhere.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] Some states in the United States currently require the exit signs to be colored red, despite the usage of color red in signage usually implies hazards, prohibited actions or stop, while the color green implies safe place/actions or to proceed.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] Older building code in Canada required red exit signs, but no new installation is allowed.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] An emergency door release call point (or a pull station in the United States) is used to disengage locking devices such as electromagnets, bolt locks, and electric locks while also ensuring positive security and failsafe operation.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] Worldwide, there have been repeated mass casualties in nightclubs and related venues where large numbers of people may gather.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] A violent personal dispute, fire, terrorist attack, or other incident can cause a mass panic or stampede for the exits.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] If the exits are blocked, locked, hidden, or inadequate, large numbers of casualties and deaths can result.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] The 1942 Cocoanut Grove fire in Boston caused over 400 deaths from a flash fire in a blacked-out nightclub with only a single obvious exit through a revolving door.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] Building codes and life safety regulations were extensively reformed in the US in the following years, and influenced changes in many other countries as well.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] However, mass casualty incidents still occur in the United States and elsewhere in the world, due to inadequate enforcement of safety rules.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] For a list of some of the most notable incidents, see Template:Club fires.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] Firefighters have cited overzealous security guards who told people during a fire that they are not allowed to use emergency exits.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] The practice is actually quite common in the absence of fires, as well.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] Some skyscrapers have stairwells with standard emergency exit signs on each door, which then lock upon closing.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] Users of these stairwells can get trapped if they do not know that the only door that opens from the inside is the one on the ground floor.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] A further problem becoming very common in the United States as of 2005 is that retail stores at night close one of their main entrance/exits through makeshift heavy metal barriers, signage, paper notes, or junk placed in front of the exits.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] A large array of signage and mechanical exit systems have also been devised, including signage that says contradictorily, "Not an exit", "Do not exit", "This is not an exit", "Do not use this exit", or warning users that a heavy penalty will be assessed for non-emergency use.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] Some systems do not allow the exit to be opened until the user signals the intention to exit (through a button or lever) for some amount of time, such as 20 seconds.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] It is also common for these exits to remain completely locked until somebody tests them.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] Some have alarms activated when they are opened, to alert staff of unauthorized use during non-emergencies.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] On many exits, the user may have to push against a crash bar or other door opening device for a period of time to unlock the door.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] Many exits have a sign reading, "Emergency exit only, alarm will sound if opened", to warn of the fact that it is an emergency exit only.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] In aircraft terms, an "exit" is any one of the main doors (entry doors on the port side of the aircraft and service doors on the starboard side) and an "emergency exit" is defined as an exit that is only ever used in an emergency (such as overwing exits and permanently-armed exits).
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] In the early years, the emergency exit was a hatch in the ceiling of the aircraft.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] Because in the 1928 KLM Fokker F.III Waalhaven crash the passengers did not know the location of this emergency exit, one passenger could not escape in time and died.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] As a result, better visibility of the emergency exit inside the cabin was advised by the investigative committee.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] Passengers seated in exit rows may be called upon to assist and open exits in the event of an emergency.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] The number and type of exits on an aircraft is regulated through strict rules within the industry, and is based on whether the aircraft is single or twin-aisled; the maximum passenger load; and the maximum distance from a seat to an exit.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] The goal of these regulations is to make possible the evacuation of an airliner's designed maximum occupancy of passengers and crew within 90 seconds even if half of the available exits are blocked.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] Any aircraft where the emergency exit door sill height is above that which would make unaided escape possible is fitted with an automatic inflatable evacuation slide, which allows occupants to slide to the ground safely.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] Ventral exits must allow the same rate of egress as a Type I exit, tailcone exit are aft of the fuselage.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] Aircraft for less than 19 passenger must have one sufficient exit in each side of the fuselage, two per side for more, no more than 60 ft (18 m) apart from each other.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] In November 2019, the EASA allowed "Type-A+" exits with a dual-lane evacuation slide to increase maximum accommodation increased to 480 seats up from 440 with four pairs of doors on the A350-1000, and up to 460 on the A330-900.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] Following the events of the Victoria Hall disaster in Sunderland, England, in 1883 in which more than 180 children died because a door had been bolted at the bottom of a stairwell, the British government began legal moves to enforce minimum standards for building safety.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] This slowly led to the legal requirement that venues must have a minimum numbers of outward opening emergency exits as well as locks which could be opened from the inside.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] These moves were not globally copied for some time.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] For example, in the United States, 146 factory workers died in the Triangle Shirtwaist Factory fire in 1911 when they were stopped by locked exits, and 492 people died in the Cocoanut Grove fire in a Boston nightclub in 1942.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] This led to regulations requiring that exits of large buildings open outward, and that enough emergency exits be provided to accommodate the building's capacity.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] Similar disasters around the world also resulted in public fury and calls for changes to emergency regulations and enforcement.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] An investigation was launched by the Argentine federal government after 194 people were killed during the 2004 República Cromañón nightclub fire in Buenos Aires, Argentina.
[src:emergency-exit/emergency-exit] The emergency exits had been chained shut by the owners, to prevent people from sneaking into the club without paying.
